  "prompt": "What is infant mortality rate?",
  "response": "Infant mortality rate (IMR) is a key demographic indicator that measures the number of deaths of infants under one year of age per 1,000 live births in a given year. It is used to assess the overall health and well-being of a population, as well as the effectiveness of healthcare systems, maternal health, and socioeconomic conditions. A high IMR often suggests underlying issues such as poor access to healthcare, malnutrition, infectious diseases, and inadequate prenatal and postnatal care. Conversely, a low IMR typically indicates better healthcare services and general living conditions.",
